<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Visuals</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:  The engine is absolutely amazing... period.  Even with my GF2 the graphics are spectacular.  The landscape and models are highly detailed, and animations are smooth and don't look out of place.  During combat as you take damage your armor and body will reflect how damaged you are (dent, scratches, blood).  Grass/shrubery (which can be turned off), water reflections and shore effects, add to emersion.  All graphical effects including brightness, resolution, etc can be changed in game on the fly (THANK YOU).  And oh ya, you can play in windowed mode.  <br>
<br>
You'll need a decent system to run AC2.  733mhz and a GeForce+ is recommended.  On my system (900mhz, GF2) I run with Texture/Model settings at high, draw distance medium, full sky effects, no water effects (reflections, shore effects), and volumetric player shadows set to my character only.  At 1024x768 with these settings the game runs smoothly enough (this isn't at twitch game like Quake) and I've never been distracted by jerky graphics.  There's also an option to let the game automatically reduce your settings if your system begins to lug.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Sound</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:  There seem to be times when ambiant noises and ingame music are missing when they shouldn't be, but when it IS there it fits the setting but isn't distracting.  I've noticed on two occasions that the sound became scratchy and distorted... possibly some compatibility issues that need to be worked out.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Interface</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:  Very intuitive.  Easy to figure out without having to read a manual.  All windows are represented by icons with easily distinguishable images on them (for instance, a Key for quests, an Anvil for skills, a Magnifying glass for the Examine &quot;skill&quot;).  All keys are bindable and the camera is easily adjusted to fit your play style.  You can zoom hundreds of feet out from your character or right up so you're looking right over your shoulder.  Mouselook is also an option (default activated by 3rd mouse button).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Combat</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:  Incredibly simple.  Targetting a creature and hitting autoattack causes your character to a) run up and start swinging or b) start shooting it.  Special abilities/combat skills can be dragged from your skill tree to your hotkey bar.  Some attacks require that your target be &quot;vulnerable&quot; or that you use another skill before it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Skills</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:  Divided up in 5 categories.  Melee, Missle, Magic, Passive, Trade.  Everytime you level up you gain a Skill Credit which can be used to open a new skill for your use.  As you kill mobs you gain XP.  That XP can be assigned to any skill in any skill tree as long as the skill has been opened.  Currently the skill trees seem very unbalanced... but that's what beta is for right?  Skill in the Trade category is gained by actually crafting items, not by assigning XP.  I haven't yet used any of the Passive type skills so I can't comment on them.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Trade</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:  All items fromt he very beginning of the game (minus starting gear) have component values.  For instance, a Tier 1 sword might have an iron value of 23.  When you start life as a tradesman you begin by collecting n00b loot and using their components to create new items.  For instance, the first swords you are able to make as a Lugian are Scythes (cool lookin curved swords).  They require 15 iron.  If you find an item with that component value, you place it in the item slot, hit craft, your character bangs his hands together and you may or may not come out with a new item.  If you fail to create a new item, you lose whatever you were crafting from.<br>
<br>
As you advance in skill you will need to either level up to get better drops or start mining.  There are mines scattered all over Dereth.  Stone, Iron, Wood and Crystal mines.  Mines are usually in out of the way locations, but you won't have to run all the way across the continent thanks to Dereth's portal system.<br>
<br>
For a complete guide to crafting go here:<br>
Taken from AC2 Beta Community - <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://home.attbi.com/~daeaston/AC2crafting.rtf">AC2 Crafting</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Economy</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:  Tradeskills will play a large part in the economy.  However, since the world is still in shambles and there are NO npcs it's hard for me to say how the economy will fair (especially since everyone and their mother will probably take up crafting as it's a good way to make cash I believe).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Kingdom vs Kingdom PvP</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:  There are 3 different kingdoms in Dereth, each with different ideals.  When your character is born they begin neutral, and cannot participate in KvK.  Once you join a Kingdom you will be able to partake in battles over different areas in Dereth.  I cannot comment on the balance or workings of KvK as I have not participated in it at this time.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> The World</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:  The world of Dereth is vast and beautiful...... and empty.  Thanks god for the portal system.  I think I'd go insane if I had to run everywhere.<br>
<br>
With all that said, I honestly doubt that I will buy this game.  While the game (and more specifically the game's engine) has massive potential, there is NOTHING to do but hack, slash, and turn your loot into gold or use it for trade (though keep in mind I've not experinced the mid/highend game).  Quests I've found thus far include &quot;Kill 10 [insert mob]&quot; and &quot;Travel through the portal, find the Ruby Obelisk and touch it.&quot;  The backstory is thus.  The world was destroyed, and everyone is coming out of their caves to rebuild it.  The original Asheron's Call is most famous for it's huge world shaping quests and events.  If Turbine continues this tradition the game might have some draw.  Vault Quests are supposedly in the game but I've yet to find any.  The only one I've spotted on my map wasn't actually there... go figure.  Then again, the game has another month of beta or so... maybe it'll get a bit more interesting. <p>Kahine sez "teh k00ky d4rg0n hed pwnz0r teh eye eblbem w00t!!1"</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#EBEFF1><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uzato.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zato</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Head Whip Cracker</span><br>  Posts: 876<br> <font color=#000000>(8/30/02 11:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ftmalliance99801frm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=18.topic&index=1>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://home.sprintmail.com/~tarvin/zatolionsm.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Asheron's Call 2</span><hr size=1> Nice writeup Khaine!<br>
